WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.720
 - Hello and welcome to a code walkthrough for C programming for everybody.

00:00:05.720 --> 00:00:11.620
 The code we're walking through is some of the epilogue code where we're comparing kind

00:00:11.620 --> 00:00:19.620
 of what I did in my chapter six Kearney and O'Ritchie stuff to what Guido tells us was

00:00:19.620 --> 00:00:29.060
 the Python 1 and then later the Python 3.7 approach to dictionaries, lists, and strings.

00:00:29.060 --> 00:00:32.860
 So what I'm going to go through right in this one is the string.

00:00:32.860 --> 00:00:35.420
 So let's take a look at that code.

00:00:35.420 --> 00:00:41.680
 This is basically the code that is the string code.

00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:48.820
 Now the pattern that I'm using here is a chunked array of characters.

00:00:48.820 --> 00:00:53.500
 And so like if you look at it, the string has some data.

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:57.760
 But what we're adding for this particular one was something that Guido was very obsessed

00:00:57.760 --> 00:01:02.220
 with in the early Python version, again from ABC.

00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:07.340
 And the idea is that we use this thing called reference counting.

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:11.980
 And it means that if you sort of assign something, you don't always have to copy all the data.

00:01:11.980 --> 00:01:18.100
 You can kind of copy a pointer instead, but then you have to be careful that reference

00:01:18.100 --> 00:01:25.300
 count because the del operation has to know when the reference count goes to zero.

00:01:25.300 --> 00:01:32.140
 So this pretty much looks like the code that I wrote sort of for the K&R book to implement

00:01:32.140 --> 00:01:35.100
 it with some reference counting.

00:01:35.100 --> 00:01:42.000
 And the easiest thing to do is look at the main code here.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.100
 And so we create a new string.

00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:49.100
 We dump it.

00:01:49.100 --> 00:01:51.820
 We add an H character.

00:01:51.820 --> 00:01:53.420
 We dump it.

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:58.100
 We add LOWorld as a string, and we dump it.

00:01:58.100 --> 00:02:02.060
 And then we're going to set it to a new value.

00:02:02.060 --> 00:02:05.340
 But then here's the new part right here.

00:02:05.340 --> 00:02:08.020
 We're going to create this assignment.

00:02:08.020 --> 00:02:15.620
 And so this we're creating, we have a variable called x, which is a pointer to a P1STR.

00:02:15.620 --> 00:02:19.760
 And we have a variable called y, which is also a pointer to a P1STR.

00:02:19.760 --> 00:02:27.240
 So what this is is this is P1STR_ASSIGN, and we're passing in a pointer.

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:31.260
 And so what's going to happen here is this is like, I'm going to increment the reference

00:02:31.260 --> 00:02:32.260
 count.

00:02:32.260 --> 00:02:33.260
 You're going to see this.

00:02:33.260 --> 00:02:37.100
 It's going to increment the reference count because now we're going to have two variables,

00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:41.060
 x and y, that are literally pointing to the same string.

00:02:41.060 --> 00:02:45.500
 So let's even run this code, okay?

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:49.220
 So I've got it run here.

00:02:49.220 --> 00:02:56.420
 And so what we see in that last bit, when we make all the top bit here, is all on the

00:02:56.420 --> 00:02:57.420
 string x.

00:02:57.420 --> 00:03:01.500
 But the interesting part here is where we say string x equals a completely new string,

00:03:01.500 --> 00:03:05.120
 and we're pointing out the location in memory that that is.

00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:09.860
 And then after the assignment statement, we see string y equals a completely new string,

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:11.920
 and it's at the same location.

00:03:11.920 --> 00:03:15.620
 But what we've done is we have incremented the reference count.

00:03:15.620 --> 00:03:22.060
 Then if you look at the main code, we del x, which was the original P1STR del x, which

00:03:22.060 --> 00:03:23.280
 is the original one.

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:29.740
 And all we do is we decrement the reference count, but we don't actually deallocate data.

00:03:29.740 --> 00:03:32.620
 And then we still have the string y.

00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:34.620
 We shouldn't have the string x.

00:03:34.620 --> 00:03:43.340
 But then what happens when we delete y at the very end here, P1STR_DEL_Y, then it actually

00:03:43.340 --> 00:03:45.860
 frees the data.

00:03:45.860 --> 00:03:53.540
 And so the idea is we can copy a reference without copying all the data, have x pointing

00:03:53.540 --> 00:03:57.460
 to it, y pointing to it, with a reference count of 2.

00:03:57.460 --> 00:03:59.700
 And then we can free either x or y.

00:03:59.700 --> 00:04:03.140
 Instead of throwing away the data, that decrements the reference count.

00:04:03.140 --> 00:04:06.740
 So let's just sort of take a bit of a look.

00:04:06.740 --> 00:04:10.980
 Now most of this is the same as what we covered.

00:04:10.980 --> 00:04:22.140
 Like if we look at sort of the constructor, P1STR new, we allocate a buffer.

00:04:22.140 --> 00:04:23.660
 We allocate the object.

00:04:23.660 --> 00:04:26.260
 And then we allocate 10 bytes.

00:04:26.260 --> 00:04:28.340
 And we tell it that it's 10 long.

00:04:28.340 --> 00:04:32.700
 And we put a new end of string in there.

00:04:32.700 --> 00:04:34.440
 And we set the reference count to 1.

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:40.360
 So as soon as we create it, we assume that this new is going to be assigned into a variable.

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:43.260
 And then we make the reference count be 1.

00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:50.320
 And so if you look at the land and the dump and the et cetera, and you look at the append,

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:55.580
 we see the append is pretty much a clone of what I did, where if we don't have enough

00:04:55.580 --> 00:05:01.620
 space, we allocate another block of 10, as Guido calls this chunking in the video.

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:03.100
 And then we reallocate it.

00:05:03.100 --> 00:05:04.460
 And then we've got 10 more.

00:05:04.460 --> 00:05:09.380
 And so we can stick our character in to the end of it and add 1 to it.

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:11.860
 And then we null terminate the string.

00:05:11.860 --> 00:05:20.120
 So that code is identical to what I did in the Carnegie and Ritchie book.

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:25.040
 And so let's look at the assign code.

00:05:25.040 --> 00:05:34.940
 So this is the interesting thing, where P1STR_ASSIGN, we have one pointer.

00:05:34.940 --> 00:05:37.380
 And we're going to return this pointer.

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:43.320
 So we have two variables pointing to the same block of dynamically allocated memory.

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:50.900
 So when we're doing this assignment statement, in effect, y equals x, inside the object,

00:05:50.900 --> 00:05:52.600
 we don't need to worry too much about y or x.

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:56.980
 But we do need to know that we are now referenced two places.

00:05:56.980 --> 00:06:02.900
 So every time we reference at a second or third reference, we just add 1 to the reference

00:06:02.900 --> 00:06:03.900
 count.

00:06:03.900 --> 00:06:05.820
 So self arrow refs plus plus.

00:06:05.820 --> 00:06:07.100
 And then we return it.

00:06:07.100 --> 00:06:12.340
 So then if we look at the code in the main program, where we're saying struct P1STR star

00:06:12.340 --> 00:06:18.180
 y equals P1STR_ASSIGN x, we could have said y equals x.

00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:22.940
 But we wanted to record the fact that we've added a reference so that we know that that

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:24.300
 has reference count of 2.

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:27.860
 So we don't inadvertently free the wrong thing.

00:06:27.860 --> 00:06:32.540
 And then the only other place that this gets interesting is in the Dell method.

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:36.380
 So if we go into the Dell method, what's cool about this?

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:43.260
 And this is where reference counts-- and so in our main code, we delete y with an underscore

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:44.260
 Dell method.

00:06:44.260 --> 00:06:45.260
 We delete x.

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:46.360
 We can do all that stuff.

00:06:46.360 --> 00:06:50.540
 And it's inside the object where these reference counts are being resolved.

00:06:50.540 --> 00:06:55.440
 And so what's cool about this is we're saying, OK, we're going to Dell x, which was the original

00:06:55.440 --> 00:06:58.400
 thing that we assigned it into.

00:06:58.400 --> 00:07:04.060
 And if the reference are greater than 1, we don't actually free any data.

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:07.540
 We just decrement the reference count, and we're done.

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:11.580
 And so that's where we see in the output, we see decrementing reference.

00:07:11.580 --> 00:07:19.500
 And you see all these addresses are the same-- 0, x, 6, 0, blah, blah, blah, 9, 1, c, 0.

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:21.620
 And so they're being decremented.

00:07:21.620 --> 00:07:24.880
 And so the first free decrements it.

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:30.980
 And that goes from 2 to 1, in this case, because the underscore assign incremented it.

00:07:30.980 --> 00:07:33.500
 And then the underscore Dell decremented it.

00:07:33.500 --> 00:07:39.620
 But then when we get the ref count to 1, that means we're, in effect, freeing the last reference.

00:07:39.620 --> 00:07:41.780
 So it prints out freeing reference.

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:43.020
 And you can see it says freeing.

00:07:43.020 --> 00:07:45.120
 We're actually freeing the data.

00:07:45.120 --> 00:07:47.700
 And so that's where we do the free of self data.

00:07:47.700 --> 00:07:53.060
 And then we free the self to get rid of it, which is the code we did before.

00:07:53.060 --> 00:08:04.660
 And so the real essence of this code is the obsession with reference counting.

00:08:04.660 --> 00:08:09.060
 And that has to do with the fact that you want to be able to point multiple places to

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:14.500
 the same string without wasting extra memory just to make a bunch of copies for no real

00:08:14.500 --> 00:08:15.500
 purpose.

00:08:15.500 --> 00:08:20.620
 So when you're kind of making a copy that points to the original, then you have to increment

00:08:20.620 --> 00:08:24.180
 the reference count and decrement it.

00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:29.540
 And so in the rest of these sample code, I will not add reference counting to it because

00:08:29.540 --> 00:08:32.100
 we're just going to look at the underlying data structures.

00:08:32.100 --> 00:08:39.980
 But it's really important to understand that reference counting was essential to the ABC

00:08:39.980 --> 00:08:48.740
 implementation and Guido's C++ implementation and Python 1.0's implementation.

00:08:48.740 --> 00:08:54.500
 It was all about reference counting to save very scarce memory so that you could point

00:08:54.500 --> 00:08:58.980
 to the same string many times, and the reference counts could get very high, especially strings

00:08:58.980 --> 00:09:00.700
 that were constants.

00:09:00.700 --> 00:09:05.140
 So reference counting is important, and this is just-- you can take a look at this code

00:09:05.140 --> 00:09:09.200
 and compare it to the KR code that I built.

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:21.580
 Reference counting is an important part of Python.

